Beta proportion distribution

Jussi Huotari

2020-11-27

Stan has Beta Proportion Distribution for modeling a continuous random variable that takes values between (0, 1). The distribution was implemented in stan-dev/math#914.

The parameters are mu and kappa, where \(\mu \in (0,1)\) and \(\kappa > 0\).

\[\begin{aligned} \mu & = \frac{\alpha}{\alpha+\beta} \\ \kappa & = \alpha+\beta \end{aligned}\]

For example, if \(\alpha = 2\) and \(\beta = 8\), then \(\mu = 0.2\) and \(\kappa = 10\).

Lets fit a simple linear regression to see how to use the distribution to model data.

library("ggplot2")
library("bayesplot")
library("dplyr")
library("rstan")

1 Example data

Lets simulate some Beta distributed data.

n <- 200
d <- data.frame(y = rbeta(n, 2, 8), x = 1:n)
(ggd <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_point(color = "#56B4E9DD", size = 2))

2 Model: Simple Beta

\[\begin{aligned} y & \sim BetaProportion(\mu, \kappa) \\ \mu & \sim U(0, 1) \\ \kappa & \sim N(10, 5), >0 \end{aligned}\]

stan_data <- list(N = nrow(d), y = d$y)
fit <- stan("simple_beta_proportion.stan", data = stan_data, refresh = 0,
            iter = 1000, seed = 42)
cat(get_stancode(fit))
data {
  int<lower=0> N;
  vector[N] y;     // target
}

parameters {
  real<lower=0, upper=1> mu;
  real<lower=0> kappa;
}

model {
  mu ~ uniform(0, 1);
  kappa ~ normal(10, 5);
  y ~ beta_proportion(mu, kappa);
}

generated quantities {
  vector[N] yrep;
  for (n in 1:N) {
    yrep[n] = beta_proportion_rng(mu, kappa);
  }
}
print(fit, pars = c("mu", "kappa"), probs = c(.05, .5, .95))
Inference for Stan model: simple_beta_proportion.

The model fits properly, with good Rhat and n_eff values. The plots show that posterior parameter values are close to the values used to create the simulated data set, i.e.\(\mu = 0.2\) and \(\kappa = 10\).

2.1 Plot parameter estimates

bayesplot_grid( grid_args = list(ncol=2),
  mcmc_hist(fit, pars = "mu", binwidth = .005) + vline_at(.2),
  mcmc_hist(fit, pars = "kappa", binwidth = .5) + vline_at(10)
)

yrep <- extract(fit, pars = 'yrep')$yrep
ppc_dens_overlay(d$y, yrep[1:50, ])

3 Model with predictor

Using x as a predictor, the model is

\[\begin{aligned} y_{i} & \sim BetaProportion(\mu_i, \kappa) \\ logit(\mu_i) & = a + b \times x \\ \kappa & \sim N(10, 5), >0 \end{aligned}\]

Using the same data, b should be 0. Because of the logit link function, a should be interpreted with the transformation in mind. Lets see.

logit <- function(p) log(p/(1-p))
inv_logit <- function(p) 1/(1+exp(-p))
ggplot(data = d, aes(x=x, y=logit(y))) +
  geom_point(color = "#56B4E9DD", size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Logit transformed data")

stan_data <- list(N = nrow(d), y = d$y, x = d$x)
fit <- stan("linear_beta_proportion.stan", data = stan_data, refresh = 0, 
            iter = 1000, seed = 42)
Tail Effective Samples Size (ESS) is too low, indicating posterior variances and tail quantiles may be unreliable.
Running the chains for more iterations may help. See
http://mc-stan.org/misc/warnings.html#tail-ess
cat(get_stancode(fit))
data {
  int<lower=0> N;
  vector[N] y;     // target
  vector[N] x;     // predictor
}

parameters {
  real a;
  real b;
  real<lower=0> kappa;
}

transformed parameters {
  vector[N] mu = a + b * x;
  vector[N] theta = inv_logit(mu);
}

model {
  a ~ normal(.3, .5);
  b ~ normal(0, .5);
  kappa ~ normal(10, 5);
  y ~ beta_proportion(theta, kappa);
}

generated quantities {
  vector[N] yrep;
  for (n in 1:N) {
    yrep[n] = beta_proportion_rng(theta[n], kappa);
  }
}
print(fit, pars = c("a", "b", "kappa"), probs = c(.05, .5, .95))

)

4 Data with slope

In the previous example, the predictor x had no effect. Lets spice up the data by making it a time series with a slight upward trend.

beta_with_slope <- rbeta(n, 2, 8) + seq(from = 0, to = .1, length.out = n)
d <- data.frame(y = beta_with_slope, x = 1:n)
(ggd <- ggplot(data = d, aes(x=x, y=y)) +
  geom_point(color = "#56B4E9DD", size = 2))

4.1 Fit to new data

stan_data <- list(N = nrow(d), y = d$y, x = d$x)
fit <- stan(fit = fit, data = stan_data, refresh = 0, seed = 42)
print(fit, pars = c("a", "b", "kappa"), probs = c(.05, .5, .95))

4.2 Validate the estimate

I like to refer to Robust Statistical Workflow with RStan to check the reliability of the results. The utilities are implemented conveniently in Rstan check_hmc_diagnostics

check_hmc_diagnostics(fit)

Energy:
E-BFMI indicated no pathological behavior.

4.3 Plot

bayesplot_grid( grid_args = list(ncol=2),
  mcmc_hist(fit, pars = "a", transform = inv_logit, binwidth = .005) + vline_at(.2),
  mcmc_hist(fit, pars = "kappa", binwidth = .5) + vline_at(10)
)

theta <- apply(extract(fit)$theta, 2, quantile, c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95)) %>%
  t() %>% data.frame(., x=d$x)
ggd + geom_line(data = theta, aes(y = X50.), color = "#FF99FFDD") +
  geom_ribbon(data = theta, aes(y = X50., ymin = X5., ymax = X95.), fill = "#FF99FF44")

yrep <- extract(fit, pars = 'yrep')$yrep
ppc_dens_overlay(d$y, yrep[1:50, ])

5 Conclusion

Beta proportion distribution can be used to model a bounded continuous random variable. With a logit link function its possible to build a linear model with predictors, and quite convenient to leave data transformation to the Stan code. Though its worth considering if its linear (enough) after the non-linear data transformation.

A challenge (for me) is the distributions parametrization \(\mu\) and \(\kappa\). How to intuit about \(\kappa\)? What would be a good weakly informative prior, for example?
